Bio: Cœur de Pirate, born Béatrice Martin, is a Canadian singer-songwriter recognized for her enchanting voice and introspective lyrics. Emerging onto the music scene in the mid-2000s, she quickly gained prominence for her distinct blend of pop, folk, and chanson française influences. With several critically acclaimed albums to her name, Cœur de Pirate has amassed a dedicated global following and continues to captivate listeners with her emotive storytelling and evocative melodies.

Michael Gervais is a renowned high-performance psychologist who has worked extensively with elite athletes and top professionals across sports and business to enhance performance through mental skills training. He co-founded Compete to Create with NFL coach Pete Carroll, aiming to transform organizational cultures and individuals' lives through mindfulness and psychological strategies. Gervais' approach focuses on cultivating a growth mindset, resilience, and mindfulness to achieve peak performance and well-being.

Joan Jett is an American rock singer, songwriter, and guitarist known for her work with Joan Jett & the Blackhearts. She rose to fame with hits like "I Love Rock 'n' Roll" and "Bad Reputation," embodying the rebellious spirit of punk rock. Jett's influence extends beyond music, as she's also recognized for her role in pioneering women's place in the rock genre. Her gritty vocals, distinctive guitar riffs, and unapologetic attitude have cemented her as a rock icon.

Ben Stein is a versatile American figure, recognized for his roles as an economist, actor, writer, and political commentator. He gained notoriety for his deadpan, monotone delivery in his role as the economics teacher in the movie "Ferris Bueller's Day Off." A Yale Law School alumnus, Stein also worked as a speechwriter for Presidents Nixon and Ford. His career covers a wide range, including television, movies, and political analysis, highlighting his blend of scholarly insight and entertainment.

Billy Joe Armstrong, the frontman of the punk rock band Green Day, is a prolific musician, songwriter, and advocate known for his raw energy and anthemic melodies. With a career spanning decades, Armstrong's music embodies rebellion, individualism, and social commentary. Through hits like "American Idiot" and "Basket Case," he has left an indelible mark on the music world, inspiring generations with his passionate performances and unapologetic expression of punk ethos.

Dean Schneider is a Swiss animal sanctuary founder and social media personality based in South Africa. Schneider studied finance and at age 21, became an entrepreneur. Schneider was a banker and financial planner in Switzerland before moving to South Africa in 2017 to establish a wildlife sanctuary and rehabilitation center.

Megyn Kelly is a prominent American journalist and former Fox News anchor known for her rigorous interviewing style. She gained widespread recognition for her coverage of the 2016 presidential election and clashes with then-candidate Donald Trump. Transitioning to NBC, she hosted her own morning show before facing controversies leading to its eventual cancellation. Despite setbacks in the industry, she has continued her work as a media personality and commentator including hosting her own podcast, "The Megyn Kelly Show," where she discusses current events and interviews notable guests.

Chloë Sevigny is a multifaceted American actress and fashion icon, renowned for her unique style and daring career choices. She gained critical acclaim for her debut in "Kids" and won a Golden Globe for her role in "Big Love". Sevigny's performances in indie films and mainstream projects alike have showcased her versatility and commitment to challenging roles. Beyond acting, she is known for her eclectic personal style, having made a significant impact in the fashion world. Sevigny's interests span across acting, fashion design, and activism, demonstrating her wide-ranging talents and passions.

Philip Ovadia is a cardiothoracic surgeon with a focus on preventive health and wellness, particularly in the realm of heart disease. He advocates for lifestyle changes as a primary method to prevent cardiac and metabolic diseases, emphasizing the importance of diet and exercise. Dr. Ovadia's approach combines medical expertise with a holistic view on health, aiming to reduce reliance on medications and surgeries by addressing root causes of health issues.

Kat Von D is a multifaceted American tattoo artist, entrepreneur, and television personality, best known for her work on TLC's reality show "LA Ink." Born Katherine Von Drachenberg in 1982, she has made a significant impact in the beauty industry with her eponymous makeup line, Kat Von D Beauty, renowned for its long-wear, vegan, and cruelty-free products. A vocal advocate for animal rights, her artistic talent extends beyond tattooing into music and fashion design.

Eberechi Eze, a talented English footballer, showcases a playstyle that combines technical prowess with creative vision. His skillful dribbling allows him to navigate through tight defenses effortlessly, while his acute sense of positioning and spatial awareness make him an outstanding playmaker. Eze's ability to execute precise passes and score from long distances highlights his versatility and offensive threat. His flair and agility on the pitch captivate audiences, making him a pivotal figure in the Premier League.

Tamino Amir, a Belgian-Egyptian indie rock artist. Born in 1996, Tamino gained recognition for his hauntingly soulful voice and captivating stage presence. His music often explores deep emotions and existential themes, creating a unique blend of indie, rock, and Middle Eastern influences. Tamino's debut album "Amir" was released in 2018, showcasing his remarkable talent and earning critical acclaim. With his evocative sound and introspective lyrics, Tamino has carved a distinct niche in the contemporary indie music scene.

Colin Robertson, better known as Millennial Woes, is a Scottish reactionary social and political commentator known for his controversial views on multiculturalism, race, and nationalism. Engaging through video and blogging, he facilitates discussion with the dissident right with topics such as society and culture, national identity, philosophy, religion, politics, art, and more. His content fosters a sense of community among those who share his views, however critics argue that his views are divisive and promote extremist ideologies.

Ensar Oud (real name: Ensar Gül) is a niche perfume house owner, renowned for its dedication to the ancient craft of oud distillation. The brand has gained a cult following for its artisanal approach, creating pure oud oils and oud-infused fragrances. Ensar Oud sources rare agarwood from around the world, ensuring ethical practices and the highest quality. Each scent is a journey, reflecting the rich, complex nature of oud and its cultural heritage.

Maggie Lindemann is an American singer-songwriter and model from Dallas, Texas. Gaining initial fame on social media, her music blends pop with darker, introspective themes. Her breakout single, "Pretty Girl," achieved global recognition, showcasing her vocal range and lyrical depth. Maggie's style evolves continually, reflecting her personal growth and diverse musical influences, making her a prominent figure in the contemporary pop music scene.

Klee Irwin is an American entrepreneur and researcher. He is the founder of Irwin Naturals, an natural supplement company, and the founder of Quantum Gravity Research (QGR), a non-profit research institute. Irwin is focused on developing a theory of everything that bridges quantum mechanics and general relativity. His work often explores the fringes of theoretical physics, emphasizing geometric first principles. Additionally, Irwin has a background in business, having established successful ventures in various sectors. He is also known for his involvement in educational initiatives and public speaking, where he disseminates complex scientific concepts to broader audiences. Irwin's approach combines entrepreneurial acumen with a quest for deeper understanding of the natural world.

Mario Sznajder is a distinguished academic known for his extensive work in political science. Born in Chile, he has made significant contributions to the study of authoritarian regimes, democratic transitions, and human rights in Latin America. Sznajder's research often focuses on the complexities of political ideologies and their impact on societies. He has held various academic positions and is widely respected for his insightful analysis and scholarly publications in the field.

Amalie Bruun, better known by her stage name Myrkur, is a Danish musician and model. Emerging in the black metal scene, she has gained acclaim for her unique blend of raw, atmospheric black metal with ethereal, folk-inspired melodies. Her music often features hauntingly beautiful vocals, contrasting with the genre's typically harsh sound. Bruun's work under Myrkur has been both praised and controversial, showcasing her versatility as an artist.

Sam Kerr is an Australian footballer known for her speed, agility, and goal-scoring ability. As captain of the Australian national team and a player for Chelsea in the Women's Super League, Kerr has established herself as a prominent figure in women's football. Off the field, she is known for her advocacy for gender equality and LGBTQ+ rights. Her career includes multiple Golden Boot awards, and she is generally regarded as one of the greatest female footballers of her generation.

Barry Keoghan is an Irish actor renowned for his distinctive performances in both independent films and blockbuster productions. He rose to prominence with roles in acclaimed films like "The Killing of a Sacred Deer" and "Dunkirk". He has received various accolades, including a British Academy Film Award, and was nominated for an Academy Award and two Golden Globe Awards. His unique acting style and ability to portray complex characters have garnered critical acclaim, establishing him as one of the most promising talents in contemporary cinema.

Ashley Graham is an American model and television presenter widely recognized for her influence on the body positivity and inclusivity movements in fashion. She has broken conventional beauty standards by being one of the first plus-size models to appear on the cover of major fashion magazines. Graham's advocacy for diversity and self-acceptance in the industry has made her an inspirational figure to many.

Russell Brand, born on June 4, 1975, is a multifaceted English comedian, actor, author, and activist. Rising to fame with his unique comedic style, Brand has starred in films like "Forgetting Sarah Marshall" and "Get Him to The Greek." Beyond entertainment, he is known for his outspoken views on politics, spirituality, and social issues. Brand's books, including "My Booky Wook" and "Revolution," reflect his deep thoughts on personal and societal transformation. With a charismatic stage presence, Russell Brand continues to captivate audiences with his wit and thought-provoking perspectives.

Nick Vujicic, born on December 4, 1982, is an Australian motivational speaker, author, and evangelist. Born with tetra-amelia syndrome, a rare disorder characterized by the absence of all four limbs, Vujicic has overcome extraordinary challenges to inspire millions globally. Founder of the nonprofit organization Life Without Limbs, he travels the world sharing his powerful message of hope, faith, and resilience. Through his bestselling books and compelling talks, Vujicic encourages individuals to embrace their uniqueness and find purpose despite life's adversities.

Miwa is an Archaeology graduate, currently pursuing a master's degree in Biological Anthropology. She resonates deeply with animal welfare, as she dreams of being a zookeeper or working in an animal hotel. Passionate about politics and diplomacy, Miwa balances these interests with a commitment to personal health and well-being, guided by psychology and nutrition. Her artistic pursuits span drawing, music, dance, and acting. As a multifaceted individual, Miwa blends practicality with her playful, imaginative spirit, constantly on a quest for deeper meaning and personal growth in both her professional and personal endeavors.

Seeker, a postgraduate engineering major, excels at blending together abstract thinking with practical skills. His decision-making is equally influenced by his visceral instincts as well as by a visionary insight into human psychology. This combination is expressed in his success as a professional poker player, as well as in his keyboard playing and involvement in chess tournaments. His current role as a consultant in system design also demonstrates his cognitive flexibility and a keen ability to thrive under stressful situations. As an immigrant, Seeker is a testament to resilience and adaptability. He is driven by a desire to integrate all his varied experiences into a harmonious stream that not only brings peace to himself but also makes a meaningful contribution to others.

Emerald Fennell is a versatile British actress, screenwriter, and director. She gained acclaim for her role as Camilla Parker Bowles in "The Crown" and won an Emmy for her writing on the show. Fennell also wrote and directed the dark comedy-thriller film "Promising Young Woman," receiving widespread praise and an Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay in 2021. Her talent extends across various facets of the entertainment industry.

Apashe, born John De Buck, is a Belgian-born Canadian electronic music producer renowned for his innovative blend of genres, fusing elements of dubstep, trap, and orchestral music. His distinctive sound has garnered widespread acclaim, with notable tracks like "Copter Boy" and "Good News" showcasing his prowess. Apashe's ability to seamlessly integrate classical influences with bass-heavy beats sets him apart in the electronic music scene, creating a unique sonic experience for his listeners.

Sadia Khan is a relationship coach who has dedicated her social presence to helping individuals and couples navigate the complexities of their relationships. She holds a BSc in Psychology, a Master's in Education and Developmental Psychology, Qualified Teachers Status, and Diplomas in Psychotherapy, Advanced CBT, Psychoanalysis, and Inner Child Healing. Her academic training, combined with extensive practical experience, allows her to offer well-rounded and evidence-based guidance.

Tilda Swinton, born in London in 1960, is an award-winning actress known for her chameleon-like performances. With a career spanning decades, Swinton has garnered acclaim for her roles in films like "Orlando," "Michael Clayton," and "We Need to Talk About Kevin." Her collaboration with director Luca Guadagnino in films such as "I Am Love" and "A Bigger Splash" has further showcased her talent. Beyond acting, Swinton is recognized for her avant-garde style and artistic endeavors, including performance art. She has collaborated with artists, filmmakers, and photographers on different creative ventures. While not a traditional model, she is often celebrated for her distinctive androgynous style, which has made her a unique and influential figure in both the realms of cinema and art.

Jude Law is a famous English actor renowned for his versatile performances in film, theater, and television. With a career spanning decades, Law has earned critical acclaim and numerous accolades, including Academy Award nominations. His notable films include "The Talented Mr. Ripley," "Cold Mountain," and "Sherlock Holmes." Law's charismatic presence, chiseled features, and compelling acting make him a prominent figure in the entertainment industry.

Greta Gerwig is an American actress, writer, and director, acclaimed for her roles in films like "Frances Ha" and "Lady Bird." As a solo filmmaker, she wrote and directed the coming-of-age hits "Lady Bird" and "Little Women," both receiving Academy Award nominations for Best Picture. Gerwig's directorial success continued with "Barbie" (2023) which became the first film from a solo female director to gross over $1 billion worldwide.

Sufjan Stevens is an American singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist known for his genre-defying music that seamlessly blends folk, indie, and electronic elements. His introspective and emotionally charged lyrics often explore personal and universal themes. Stevens gained widespread recognition with albums like "Illinois" and "Carrie & Lowell." Known for his intricate arrangements and poetic storytelling, he has left an indelible mark on contemporary indie folk music, earning critical acclaim and a dedicated fanbase for his experimental and soul-stirring compositions.

Lorraine Warren (1927-2019) was a renowned paranormal investigator, author, and lecturer, best known for her pioneering work in the field of supernatural phenomena. Alongside her husband, Ed Warren, she investigated thousands of cases, inspiring books and films such as "The Conjuring" series. Lorraine's expertise in demonology and her commitment to helping those affected by the supernatural earned her widespread recognition and respect. With a career spanning over five decades, she became a leading authority in the paranormal community and left a lasting legacy, contributing significantly to the understanding and documentation of unexplained phenomena.

Saoirse Ronan is a famous Irish-American actress who received numerous accolades, including several Academy Award nominations for roles in films like "Atonement," "Brooklyn," and "Lady Bird." Known for her versatility and emotional depth, she became a prominent figure in the film industry, earning praise for her talent, grace, and range in various roles. Beyond her acting career, Saoirse Ronan is a committed advocate for causes addressing homelessness, domestic violence, and LGBT rights.

Anya Taylor-Joy is a famous Argentine-British actress who won several accolades, including a Golden Globe Award and a Screen Actors Guild Award. Known for her striking appearance and versatile talent, she gained widespread recognition for her roles in films like "The Witch" (2015) and "Split" (2016). Taylor-Joy further solidified her success with the critically acclaimed Netflix series "The Queen's Gambit" (2020), where her captivating performance as chess prodigy Beth Harmon earned her widespread acclaim and awards recognition.

Dr. Tara Swart is a neuroscientist, leadership coach, and author known for her expertise in the field of neuroscience and its application to leadership and personal development. With a background in medicine, she combines scientific insights with practical strategies to enhance cognitive performance, resilience, and well-being. Dr. Swart has authored books, delivered talks, and worked with individuals and organizations to optimize mental and emotional capabilities for improved success and fulfillment.

Ben Francis is the founder and CEO of Gymshark, a billion-dollar fitness apparel and accessories brand based in the UK. He started Gymshark in 2012 as a small operation, and under his leadership the brand grew rapidly, becoming a prominent player in the activewear industry. Francis utilized social media marketing strategies, particularly influencer collaborations, to propel Gymshark's success. His innovative approach to e-commerce and fitness fashion has earned him recognition as a young and influential business figure.

Stephen Wiltshire is an extraordinary British architectural artist renowned for his unique ability to draw detailed cityscapes from memory after brief observations. Born in London in 1974, he was diagnosed with autism at an early age. Wiltshire's savant syndrome endowed him with an incredible visual memory that has amazed audiences worldwide. His talent was recognized at the age of eight, and he has since gained international fame for his panoramic sketches. Despite his limited verbal communication, his art speaks volumes, capturing the essence of iconic metropolises with precision and soul.

Emily Blunt is a famous British actress known for her versatile performances. She gained recognition in "The Devil Wears Prada" (2006) and received critical acclaim for roles in "A Quiet Place" (2018) and "Mary Poppins Returns" (2018). Blunt has won various awards, including a Golden Globe.

Dave Asprey, a biohacker, entrepreneur, and "lifestyle guru," is known for popularizing the Bulletproof Coffee trend. He is the founder of Bulletproof 360 and Bulletproof Nutrition, focusing on health and performance optimization. Asprey authored books on biohacking, advocating for diet and lifestyle changes. Despite controversies surrounding his claims, his impact on the biohacking community is significant, promoting practices to enhance physical and mental well-being through innovative approaches.

Eartha Kitt (1927-2008) was a multifaceted artist known for her sultry voice and captivating stage presence. She achieved success as a singer, actress, and dancer, earning accolades like two Emmy Awards and a Tony nomination. Her most iconic role was as Catwoman in the 1960s Batman TV series. Eartha Kitt was also a committed activist, focusing on issues like civil rights and social justice throughout her life.

Denis Villeneuve, a Canadian filmmaker, is known for his meticulous craftsmanship and compelling storytelling. His notable works include "Prisoners," "Arrival," "Blade Runner 2049," and "Dune," earning critical acclaim and commercial success. Villeneuve's accomplished career has garnered multiple Academy Award nominations. He is particularly interested in science fiction and exploring the human condition through his films, solidifying his reputation as a leading figure in contemporary cinema.

Eva zu Beck is a Polish-British travel vlogger, presenter, and social media influencer known for her immersive and authentic travel content. With a focus on lesser-known destinations and cultural experiences, she shares her adventures through captivating storytelling and insightful vlogs. Eva's content offers viewers a glimpse into diverse cultures, traditions, and lifestyles, promoting a deeper understanding and appreciation of the world's cultural richness and natural beauty.

Sofiane Pamart is a French pianist originally from Hellemmes near Lille, now based in Paris. He is recognized for challenging traditional notions of classical piano, diverging from the standard classical music path despite his gold medal from the Conservatoire de Lille.  Alongside his solo career, he is also renowned as a go-to pianist in the French rap scene. Sofiane's ability to fuse classical and contemporary elements has made him a sought-after musician in the French music industry.

Mia Goth is a talented British actress known for her unique and enigmatic on-screen presence. She gained recognition for her roles in films like "Nymphomaniac" and "A Cure for Wellness." Goth is recognized for her unique style and commitment to unconventional characters, earning her a strong reputation as a compelling performer.

Theo James is a popular English actor who gained international recognition for his role as Tobias "Four" Eaton in The Divergent Series. Beyond acting, he was a singer and guitarist in the indie rock band Shere Khan. He is also a brand ambassador for Hugo Boss fragrances for men, and an advocate for refugee rights and humanitarian aid.

Tom Holland is a famous British actor best known for his portrayal of Spider-Man in the Marvel Cinematic Universe. With his charismatic charm, youthful energy, and impressive agility, Holland has become a beloved figure among fans of the superhero genre. Beyond his acting career, Holland stands out as a passionate advocate for several charitable causes, including children's hospitals and disaster relief efforts, demonstrating a strong commitment to making a positive impact beyond the silver screen.

Richard Kuklinski, known as the "Iceman," was an infamous American contract killer and serial murderer. Born in 1935, he led a double life as a devoted family man and a ruthless criminal. Kuklinski's cold-blooded nature earned him his chilling nickname, as he committed countless homicides for organized crime syndicates. His deadly career spanned several decades before his arrest in 1986. Kuklinski's life and crimes continue to fascinate and horrify, making him a notorious figure in the annals of true crime history. He died in prison in 2006, leaving behind a legacy of darkness and violence.

Jesse Eisenberg, an American actor and writer, achieved fame for portraying Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg in "The Social Network" (2010). His impressive work has earned him nominations for an Academy Award, two BAFTA Awards, and a Golden Globe Award. Beyond his film career, Eisenberg has also authored several plays and books.

Martin Shkreli is an American former pharmaceutical executive known for his controversial actions in the pharmaceutical industry. Born in 1983, he worked in the pharmaceutical and financial industries, co-founding hedge funds and starting pharmaceutical companies. He gained notoriety in 2015 for raising the price of a life-saving drug by over 5,000%. His decision to raise the price of Daraprim, a drug used to treat parasitic infections, sparked outrage and legal issues. In 2017, he was convicted on securities fraud and conspiracy charges, resulting in a prison sentence. Shkreli's actions and public persona have made him a controversial figure.

Founder of actualized.org (founding is a theme for the Ti function), Leo had a lot of struggles earlier in life like lack of motivation, fears, destructive habits, and lack of consistency in his work. Because of this, he got into the self-help genre and used it to try to improve every aspect of his life via self-mastery (a major Fe-Ti axis theme). He studied a huge range of self-help information, 10000 dollars worth a year, which speaks to his novelty seeking Pe function as the leading process. He tried many things without getting clear results, but eventually he found a set of techniques that he believes cause radical improvement and he wants to share them with others to help everyone reach their potential (Ne+Fe potentialist theme), though he is always expanding this. Now he is a quite successful life coach with his own creative business and set of principles, and he is a content creator (another major theme for Ne dominant people) who makes videos on dating, sexuality, practical life advice, spirituality, politics and society, metaphysics and epistemology, psychedelics and developmental psychology.

Christoph Waltz is a renowned Austrian actor who gained international acclaim for his roles in Quentin Tarantino's films "Inglourious Basterds" (2009) and "Django Unchained" (2012), winning Academy Awards for Best Supporting Actor for both performances. In addition to his acting prowess, Waltz is known for his passion for languages and is fluent in several, including German, English, and French, which has further enriched his ability to portray complex characters and solidified his place as a respected figure in the film industry.

N.K. Jemisin is a renowned American author known for her groundbreaking work in science fiction and fantasy. Her most popular works include "The Broken Earth Trilogy," which redefines the post-apocalyptic genre, and "The Inheritance Trilogy," an epic exploration of power and gods in a meticulously crafted world. With a focus on social justice and diversity, she has won numerous awards, including three consecutive Hugo Awards for Best Novel, a testament to her innovative storytelling and powerful narratives. Jemisin's writing explores themes of oppression and resilience, making her a vital voice in contemporary speculative fiction.

Fernanda Pistelli is a Brazilian DJ/Producer known for her style of mystical and psychedelic techno and hypnotic live sets at festivals such as Boom in Portugal and Universo Parallelo in Brazil. She is passionate about different ways of interpreting the universe through her senses, and music allows her to explore sensations capable of creating a unique atmosphere. She believes that music is the universal language of love and hopes to touch people’s emotions through her work. Pistelli graduated in music production from Anhembi Morumbi University in São Paulo and is currently one of Brazil's rising female talents.

Darren Slade is a theological historian, systematician, and critical rationalist philosopher from Denver, Colorado. Specializing in historic-speculative theology, theoretical metaphysics, and the socio-political development of religious belief systems, Darren’s academic publications include investigations into Islamic history, church history, ancient Near-Eastern textual interpretations, and the academic study of the philosophy, sociology, and psychology of religion. He holds a PhD in theology and church history from the Rawlings School of Divinity, and teaches ancient history and comparative religion at the Rocky Mountain College of Art and Design.

Mark Z. Danielewski is a renowned American author known for his innovative and experimental approach to storytelling. His works, including "House of Leaves" and "Only Revolutions," showcase his distinctive narrative style, which involves unconventional page layouts, footnotes, and multimedia elements. Danielewski's passion for literature, music, and visual arts is evident in his works, reflecting a multidisciplinary approach that has earned him critical acclaim and a devoted fan base, solidifying his status as a literary pioneer.

Persuader is a South Korean YouTuber and host of Lope TV (@Lope666), a place created for "Easy to Learn Politics." Persuader's focus is on simplifying intricate political concepts, making them accessible to a broad audience. He is a young, right-leaning political commentator with a pro-capitalist mindset. He discusses methods for being successful and achieving your dreams. In addition to these topics, he also occasionally discusses pop culture, celebrities and video game streaming.

Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, also known as "MVL", is a French chess sensation known for his aggressive and tactical style of play. He achieved the title of grandmaster at age 14 and has gone on to represent France in numerous international competitions. His games are characterized by sharp openings, tactical brilliance, and unpredictability. He consistently competes against the world's highest rated players and with a peak rating of 2819, he is the seventh-highest rated player in history making him a prominent figure in the world of chess.

Thiago Silva is a Brazilian footballer known for his exceptional defensive skills and leadership on the field. His main strengths are his composure, anticipation, tackling, and aerial ability. As a central defender, he has been a key figure in winning multiple league titles with clubs like AC Milan, Paris Saint-Germain, and Chelsea FC. Silva's crowning achievement came in 2021 when he captained Chelsea to victory in the UEFA Champions League, showcasing his leadership on the grandest stage. Off the pitch, he enjoys spending time with his family and is an avid music enthusiast.

Conor McGregor, the Irish mixed martial artist, boasts a remarkable MMA career. He became the first fighter in UFC history to hold titles in two weight classes simultaneously, featherweight and lightweight. McGregor's striking prowess, trash-talking ability, and self-assured demeanor have been pivotal to his success. Beyond the octagon, he's ventured into fashion and business, launching the Proper No. Twelve whiskey brand. With multiple UFC titles and record-breaking pay-per-view numbers, McGregor stands as an MMA legend.

Chris Martin, born on March 2, 1977, in the United Kingdom, is a highly accomplished musician and songwriter. He is best known as the lead vocalist and co-founder of the globally acclaimed band Coldplay. With his distinctive and emotive voice, Martin has been a driving force behind Coldplay's massive success, delivering chart-topping hits like "Yellow," "Fix You," and "Viva La Vida." His songwriting prowess has earned him numerous awards, including Grammy honors, solidifying his status as a musical icon.

Neil Gaiman is a prolific author known for his talent in the realms of fantasy and horror. With a distinct storytelling style, he has written numerous novels, short stories, comic books, and graphic novels, gaining international acclaim and a dedicated fan base. Some of his most popular works, including "American Gods," "Coraline," and "The Sandman," often explore mythology, folklore, and the supernatural. His creativity has earned him several prestigious awards, cementing his status as a prominent figure in contemporary literature.

Chris Stuckmann is a prominent YouTuber, filmmaker, and film critic known for his insightful and articulate reviews. His passion for cinema shines through in his well-researched critiques, earning him a substantial following. With over a decade of content creation, Stuckmann has amassed millions of subscribers and authored the book "The Film Buff's Bucket List," solidifying his influence in the film community. In addition to his role as a film critic, he has directed and produced several independent films, showcasing his versatility and dedication to the art of cinema.

Shérine is an officer in Fund Administration and Investment Accounting living in Luxembourg. She has a bachelor's degree in Accounting and Financial Control. However, at heart she is a Dancer, spending much of her free time at the gym or dance lessons, where she's discovered a love of jazz dance, which makes her feel at peace and relieves stress. Sherine is a deeply sensitive and compassionate person, seeking to understand the essence of life. She values loyalty and is selective about who she lets into her inner circle. She dislikes injustices, rudeness and any violence or harm caused intentionally. She has a keen interest in psychology and aspires to become a clinical therapist.

Kate Siegel is a highly acclaimed actress renowned for her captivating portrayals in the horror genre. With a penchant for complex, layered characters, she has left an indelible mark on viewers. Beyond acting, Siegel's advocacy for mental health shines, utilizing her platform to raise awareness. Her stellar accomplishments feature standout roles in hit series like "The Haunting of Hill House" and "The Haunting of Bly Manor," solidifying her status as a prominent figure in the industry.

Elvis Presley (1935-1977), often referred to as the "King of Rock and Roll," revolutionized the music and entertainment industry with his unique voice, charismatic performances, and genre-blending sound. Born in Tupelo, Mississippi, Elvis's fusion of rhythm and blues, country, and gospel led to chart-topping hits like "Heartbreak Hotel" and "Jailhouse Rock." His impact extended beyond music, with a notable acting career in Hollywood. A cultural icon of the 20th century, Presley's legacy endures, with Graceland, his Memphis home, remaining a testament to his unparalleled influence on music and pop culture.

Paul Simon, born October 13, 1941, is an American singer-songwriter with a remarkable six-decade career. He's one of the 20th century's most celebrated music artists, known for both his solo work and collaborations with Garfunkel. Simon has earned numerous accolades, including two Rock and Roll Hall of Fame inductions and sixteen Grammy Awards. Beyond music, he co-founded the Children's Health Fund, providing medical care to kids in need, showcasing his enduring influence and philanthropic efforts.

Igor is an individual on the autism spectrum from Brazil and is dedicated to the study of biology. He is currently pursuing a master's or doctorate in zoology, driven by an innate curiosity about the natural world. Beyond academia, Igor has a passion for Jungian psychology as well as animation and visual novels.

Lana Del Rey, born Elizabeth Woolridge Grant in 1985, is an American singer-songwriter known for her cinematic sound and themes of tragic romance, glamour, and melancholia. Emerging in the early 2010s with her breakout hit "Video Games," she quickly established herself as a unique voice in the music industry. Her sultry, vintage aesthetic paired with modern production creates a haunting atmosphere, earning her critical acclaim and a devoted fanbase. Throughout her career, Lana has released multiple chart-topping albums, each weaving intricate tales of love, loss, and the American dream.

Francesca Eastwood is an American actress and model born on August 7, 1993. She is the daughter of the acclaimed actor/director Clint Eastwood and actress Frances Fisher. Francesca has made a name for herself with roles in both films and television, showcasing her versatility as a performer. Notably, she has appeared in projects like "Outlaws and Angels" and TV series like "Fargo." In addition to her on-screen roles, Eastwood has made headlines for her appearances on reality TV shows and her endeavors in the modeling world, firmly establishing her own identity in the entertainment industry.

Dionna Chambers is a versatile individual with a background in NFL cheerleading, acting, modeling, and journalism. She started as an NFL cheerleader and later explored acting and modeling. She pursued an education in dance and sociology, and now she's heavily involved in fitness modeling, weight training, marketing, and life coaching. Dionna's career has taken diverse paths, reflecting her curious and multi-faceted personality.

His vast oeuvre encompasses history, politics, literature, and religion. Hitchens' atheistic perspectives were epitomized in his bestselling book "God is Not Great." His irreverent, witty commentary in publications like Vanity Fair, The Atlantic, and The Nation earned him both admirers and detractors. A fearless debater, Hitchens challenged norms and sparked dialogue on controversial topics throughout his life, becoming a compelling, albeit polarizing, figure in public discourse.

Ryan George is a Canadian comedian, actor, and content creator known for his Pitch Meetings series on the Screen Rant YouTube Channel and his self-titled comedy channel. His content features sketches and skits through which he comedically summarizes movies and TV shows, pointing out their plot holes. He often plays multiple roles in his videos, talking to himself as another character and using things like glasses, hats, and fake mustaches to distinguish between characters.

Chelsea Wolfe is an American singer-songwriter from Sacramento, California. Born on November 14, 1983, Wolfe's music blends elements of gothic rock, folk, electronic, and doom metal, creating a hauntingly distinct sound. Known for her ethereal vocals and deeply personal lyrics, Wolfe has released multiple critically acclaimed albums since her debut in 2010. Her music, often dark and atmospheric, explores themes of pain, sorrow, and the human condition, offering listeners a profound, immersive experience.

Matthew Bothwell is an astronomer at the University of Cambridge, known for his research in the field of astrophysics. Specializing in extragalactic astronomy and the study of low-mass galaxies, he is recognized for his contributions in understanding the evolution of galaxies. His work often leverages the power of cutting-edge telescopes and radio astronomy techniques. A prolific author and engaging educator, Bothwell is committed to sharing the wonders of the universe with both academic peers and the wider public.

David Tong is a renowned theoretical physicist and professor in the Department of Applied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics (DAMTP) at the University of Cambridge. His influential work primarily focuses on quantum field theory, statistical mechanics, and string theory. Known for his eloquent and engaging lectures, he has received multiple awards for his teaching and research. Dr. Tong's commitment to public education in physics is evident in his freely available online courses and extensive lecture notes.

Piers Morgan is a highly recognizable British journalist, television personality, and author. Known for his polarizing opinions and confrontational interviewing style, he has held prominent roles in media, including editor of the Daily Mirror and host of 'Piers Morgan Live' on CNN. Morgan has co-hosted 'Good Morning Britain,' and served as a judge on 'Britain's Got Talent' and 'America's Got Talent.' Notable for his unflinching critiques, his career has been marked by both controversy and significant influence in the realm of popular culture and journalism.

Jonathan Haidt is a social psychologist and Professor of Ethical Leadership at New York University's Stern School of Business. Known for his research in moral psychology, Haidt has authored significant works including "The Coddling of the American Mind" and "The Righteous Mind: Why Good People Are Divided by Politics and Religion." His contributions extend to the concept of moral foundations theory and understanding the psychological bases of ideology. As a speaker, he is regularly sought after for his unique insights into social and cultural dynamics.

Serge Haroche is a French physicist recognized for his groundbreaking work in quantum physics. Born in 1944, he achieved international acclaim for his experiments with single atoms in trap cavities, which contributed significantly to our understanding of quantum decoherence. In 2012, Haroche shared the Nobel Prize in Physics with David J. Wineland for their pioneering experiments on quantum systems. An esteemed academic, Haroche served as a professor at the College de France and contributed greatly to advancing the field of quantum information science.

Helen J. Swift is a Professor of Medieval French Studies and an Eleanor Boyle Fellow in French and EDI Fellow at St Hilda's College, Oxford University. Her interdisciplinary research spans the late medieval and early modern periods, with a focus on vernacular literature, history of the book, and visual studies of text-image relationships. Notably, her second book on identity construction and narrative voice in late medieval France was highly commended for the Society for French Studies R. Gapper Prize in 2017. In addition to her individual research, Professor Swift has contributed to various collaborative projects and held key roles in convening interdisciplinary programs at Oxford.

Kirsten Dunst is an American actress known for her versatile performances in film and television. With a career spanning over three decades, she has showcased her talent in various genres, from romantic comedies like "Bring It On" to dramatic films like "Melancholia." Dunst also gained widespread recognition for her role as Mary Jane Watson in the "Spider-Man" trilogy. Her ability to embody complex characters have solidified her as a respected and acclaimed actress in Hollywood.

Tobey Maguire is an American actor best known for his portrayal of Peter Parker/Spider-Man in the original "Spider-Man" film trilogy directed by Sam Raimi. He gained international fame and recognition for his role, which established him as a leading actor in the early 2000s. Maguire has also appeared in other notable films such as "Seabiscuit" and "The Great Gatsby," showcasing his versatility and talent as an actor.

Alex Garland is an English filmmaker and writer. He rose to prominence as a novelist in the late 1990s with his novel "The Beach," and he subsequently ventured into directing, screenwriting, and producing. Garland's notable works include "Ex Machina" and "Annihilation," which showcase his interest in exploring themes of artificial intelligence, existentialism, and the human condition. His approach to filmmaking emphasizes collaborative teamwork, as he values the collective effort of autonomous individuals working towards a common goal. Garland's work reflects his belief in pushing boundaries and challenging conventional narratives, making him a prominent figure in the movie industry.

Brian Wilson is a highly accomplished and influential American musician and songwriter. Born on June 20, 1942, he co-founded The Beach Boys and played a pivotal role in shaping the landscape of 1960s pop music. Renowned for his exceptional compositional skills, Wilson's innovative arrangements and harmonies revolutionized the industry. His timeless hits, including "Good Vibrations," "California Girls," and "God Only Knows," have solidified his status as a musical genius. Despite personal challenges and battles with mental health, Wilson remains a revered figure in the music world. His distinctive falsetto vocals and unparalleled creativity continue to inspire artists and captivate audiences worldwide.

Dame Darcy is an American cartoonist, writer, and musician. Born in 1971 in Idaho, she gained recognition in the 1990s for her comic book series, "Meat Cake." Her work, often described as Gothic and Victorian-inspired, has a distinct aesthetic that combines elements of fantasy, feminism, and historical fiction. In addition to her comics, Dame Darcy has published graphic novels and has made a mark in the world of music and performance art. Her multi-faceted creativity continues to be celebrated by a cult following.

Max Richter is a German-born British composer and pianist known for his contributions to postminimalist and contemporary classical music. He received formal training in composition from prestigious institutions such as the University of Edinburgh and the Royal Academy of Music in London, while also studying under the guidance of Italian composer Luciano Berio. He has recorded eight solo albums, and his music is widely used in cinema. Notable works include the albums "Sleep," "The Blue Notebooks," and the acclaimed soundtrack for HBO's "The Leftovers."

Brandon Boyd is an American musician, artist, and author. He is best known as the lead vocalist of the alternative rock band Incubus. Boyd's distinctive and dynamic voice, combined with his introspective and poetic lyrics, have helped establish Incubus as a prominent band in the alternative rock scene. Outside of music, Boyd is also recognized for his artistic talents, with his paintings and drawings often exploring themes of spirituality and human connection.

Eva Holbrook, also known as Lady Moon, is a versatile singer and multi-instrumentalist renowned for her work with the band SHEL. With her sisters as bandmates in SHEL, she brought an eclectic mix of folk, pop, and rock, while her solo performances under the moniker Lady Moon showcase a more intimate, ethereal side. Her soulful voice, storytelling lyrics, and mastery of instruments contribute to her distinct style and lasting impact on the music scene.

Antonia Dodge is a personality typologist and co-founder of Personality Hacker, an organization dedicated to assisting individuals in understanding their mental wiring. She's a certified Myers-Briggs practitioner and leverages typological theories to help people realize their potential. Antonia hosts various podcasts, workshops, and has many written materials which intertwine typology with personal growth and development strategies.

Andy Samberg is an acclaimed American actor, comedian, and writer. Born on August 18, 1978, he gained widespread recognition as a cast member on the television show "Saturday Night Live." Samberg's unique comedic style and infectious energy have made him a beloved figure in the entertainment industry. He has starred in numerous films and TV shows, including the hit sitcom "Brooklyn Nine-Nine," where he also served as a producer. With his sharp wit and comedic timing, Samberg continues to captivate audiences with his hilarious performances and endearing charm.

Zack Hemsey is an American composer, musician, and record producer. He is known for his work in the genres of contemporary classical, orchestral, cinematic music, and hip hop. Hemsey gained popularity through his compositions featured in film trailers, TV shows, and commercials. His music is characterized by its epic and emotionally evocative nature, often incorporating choirs and powerful orchestral arrangements. Hemsey's notable works include the album "The Way" and the song "Mind Heist," featured in the trailer for the film "Inception."

Nina Hagen is a German singer, songwriter, and actress known for her diverse and influential career in the music industry. She rose to prominence in the late 1970s and early 1980s as a pioneer of punk and new wave music. Throughout her career, Hagen has been known for her unique and avant-garde style, embracing unconventional fashion choices, theatrical makeup, and provocative stage costumes. She is celebrated for her fearlessness in expressing herself artistically and politically. Hagen's music often carries powerful messages and themes, ranging from social and political commentary to love, spirituality, and freedom of expression.

Kate Winslet is a famous British actress who gained international recognition for her roles in films such as Titanic, The Reader, and Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind. She has received various awards, including an Academy Award, a Grammy Award, two Primetime Emmy Awards, five BAFTA Awards, and five Golden Globe Awards. She is also involved in philanthropy, having co-founded the Golden Hat Foundation (a non-profit organization aiming to create autism awareness), and advocates for various social causes.

Jacques (real name Jacques Auberger) is a French music producer and performer known for his whimsical and philosophical approach to music and life. He explores various philosophical concepts and themes through his music, inviting listeners to engage with thought-provoking ideas. His music often raises questions about the nature of existence, consciousness, and the human experience. He's also known to collect and record sounds from random objects, mixing them into live DJ sets to create spontaneous and unconventional tracks that reveal the hidden beauty in everyday life. His imaginative mind and unique artistic vision have earned him a dedicated following worldwide.

Frank Zappa (1940-1993) was an American musician, composer, and satirist known for his eclectic musical style and provocative lyrics. He blended genres such as rock, jazz, and classical music, pushing boundaries and challenging societal norms. Zappa was a prolific artist, releasing numerous albums and collaborating with various musicians. His music often contained social and political commentary, humor, and criticism of mainstream culture. Zappa's unique artistic vision and uncompromising approach made him a highly influential figure in the music industry.

Cillian Murphy is an accomplished Irish actor known for his versatile performances on stage and screen. Murphy gained widespread recognition for his role as "Tommy Shelby" in the TV series "Peaky Blinders," has been nominated for a Tony Award for his work in the play "Misterman," and has received acclaim for his roles in films like "28 Days Later" and "Inception." Bryan Johnson is an American entrepreneur, venture capitalist, author, biohacker, and anti-aging practitioner. Greg O'Gallagher is a Canadian fitness entrepreneur and online personality. Sarah Shahi is an American actress and former NFL cheerleader. Born on January 10, 1980, in Euless, Texas, she is of Iranian and Spanish descent. Ken Stornes is an athlete who rose to internet fame through videos of his high altitude jumps into ice cold waters. An ex-marine, he is a trained civil economist, commander and paratrooper. Robert F. Kennedy Jr., or RFK Jr., is an influential American environmental attorney, activist, and author. Gregory Koukl is an American Christian author, speaker, radio host, and founder of "Stand to Reason", an apologetics and evangelism ministry. Bishop Robert Barron is an auxiliary bishop of the Archdiocese of Los Angeles and the founder of Word on Fire Catholic Ministries. Simone Simons, born on January 17, 1985, in Hoensbroek, Netherlands, is an internationally acclaimed singer and songwriter. Poppy (Moriah Rose Pereira), born January 1, 1995, is an American singer, songwriter, and Internet sensation. Bio: Ken Liu - a Chinese-American writer, translator, programmer, and lawyer - has made significant contributions to the science fiction and fantasy genres. Laura Marling is a critically acclaimed British folk singer-songwriter and musician. Pete Davidson (born on November 16, 1993) is an American comedian and actor, widely known for his time as a cast member on Saturday Night Live (SNL), which he joined in 2014 at the age of 20, making him one of the youngest members in the show’s history. Adama Traoré is a professional footballer known for his incredible physique, speed, and dribbling skills. Dario Nardi is a cognitive neuroscientist, researcher and lecturer known for his work in the field of personality and brain science. He taught computing and anthropology at UCLA from 1998-2012. Joshua Kenneth Richards (born January 31, 2002) is a Canadian social media personality and influencer. Gillian Anderson is an accomplished American actress renowned for her diverse roles in film, television, and theater. Megan Fox is an American actress and model known for her notable contributions to the entertainment industry. Xi Jinping is a prominent Chinese politician, serving as the General Secretary of the Communist Party of China since 2012, and the President of the People's Republic of China since 2013. Roger Scruton (1944-2020) was a prominent British philosopher who left a lasting impact on conservative thought. Steven Tyler is an iconic American musician, singer, and songwriter, best known as the lead vocalist of the rock band Aerosmith.
