Rodrigo's music career skyrocketed with her debut single "drivers license", which topped global charts in 2021, followed by her critically acclaimed debut album "Sour". Her lyrics, often drawing from personal experiences, have resonated with a wide audience, cementing her as a defining voice of her generation.

Gerald Edelman was a prominent American biologist and neuroscientist known for his groundbreaking research on the immune system and the theory of neuronal group selection. In 1972, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his contributions. Edelman's notable achievements include founding the Neurosciences Institute and developing the theory of "neural Darwinism." He dedicated his work to unraveling the intricate interactions of neurons and understanding their role in consciousness and higher cognitive functions. Throughout his career, Edelman left a lasting impact on the fields of immunology and neuroscience.

Carolyn Elliott is an acclaimed author and coach, renowned for her book "Existential Kink" which takes an unorthodox approach to self-empowerment. She holds a PhD in Critical and Cultural Studies from the University of Pittsburgh. Her work, focusing on personal transformation, integrates lesser-known spiritual practices with psychological tools. As the founder of WITCH magazine, she extends her reach beyond traditional coaching methods, utilizing a platform that intertwines self-help with esoteric and occult traditions. She brings a unique, pragmatic approach to navigating life's complexities.

Gervonta Davis is an American professional boxer who has held world championships in multiple weight classes. As of June 2023, he boasts an impressive record of 29 wins, 0 defeats, and 27 knockouts. Due to his exceptional punching power, knockout abilities, and ferocious fighting style, Davis has drawn comparisons to Mike Tyson.

Hania Rani is a Polish pianist and composer known for her emotive and contemporary style of music. With a delicate touch and expressive playing, her piano compositions evoke a range of emotions, combining elements of classical, electronic, and experimental genres. Her minimalist approach, attention to detail, and dynamic energy help create captivating performances that have garnered critical acclaim and made her an emerging figure in the contemporary music scene.

Torie Bosch is the First Opinion editor at STAT. She was previously the editor of Future Tense, a collaboration between Slate magazine, Arizona State University, and New America that covers the intersection of technology, policy, and society. She also worked as an associate editor at Slate where she edited the medical and religion departments.

Marisa LaBlue is a YouTuber who is dedicated to all things astrology, spirituality, and self-transformation. She has a YouTube channel where she teaches astrology and spirituality for self-transformation. She is also the founder of HyperThrive which aims to educate people and help their businesses thrive in the online and offline space of today’s economy.

Shohreh Aghdashloo is an Iranian-American actress who has achieved international recognition and numerous accolades, including an Emmy Award and an Academy Award nomination. Born in Tehran, she began her acting career in Iran before transitioning to Hollywood. Her regal presence, distinctive voice, and ability to convey a wide range of emotions, have helped her become a respected and admired figure in the world of acting.

Avicii, born Tim Bergling (1989-2018), was a Swedish DJ, musician, and record producer who left an indelible mark on the electronic dance music (EDM) scene. With his unique blend of melodic beats and catchy hooks, Avicii rose to international fame with chart-topping hits like "Levels" and "Wake Me Up." Known for his energetic live performances, he became an icon of EDM and inspired a generation of artists. Despite his success, Avicii battled with mental health issues and tragically passed away at the age of 28. His contributions to the music industry and his enduring legacy continue to inspire millions of fans worldwide.

Joe Dispenza is a renowned speaker, author, and educator focused on the intersection of neuroscience, epigenetics, and quantum physics. His work emphasizes the power of the mind in healing and personal transformation. He gained global recognition after appearing in the documentary "What the BLEEP Do We Know!?" Dr. Dispenza conducts workshops and training programs worldwide, teaching people to rewire their brains and recondition their bodies for a healthier and more fulfilling life. His best-selling books include "Breaking the Habit of Being Yourself" and "You Are the Placebo". He remains a pioneering figure in mind-body science.

Marina Abramović is a pioneering performance artist whose work explores the relationship between performer and audience, the limits of the body, and the possibilities of the mind. Born in Belgrade in 1946, she began her career in the early 1970s and remains one of the most influential figures in contemporary art. Her performances, which often endure for hours or days, have provoked fascination and controversy. Abramović's notable works include "Rhythm 0" (1974) and "The Artist Is Present" (2010), which solidified her standing as the "grandmother of performance art."

Brett Cooper is an American conservative political commentator, media personality, and actress. She hosts the YouTube channel The Comments Section with Brett Cooper produced by the Daily Wire. She has written for the Foundation for Economic Education and was an ambassador for PragerU and Turning Point USA. Brett Cooper began her professional acting career at the age of 10 after she moved to Los Angeles. She started in theater, and later moved on to star in film and television.

James A. Lindsay is an American author, mathematician, and public intellectual. He holds a Ph.D. in mathematics and has written extensively on various subjects, including atheism, skepticism, social justice, and critical thinking. Lindsay is known for his critical examination of ideological movements and his involvement in the "Grievance Studies Affair." He has contributed to the public discourse through his books, articles, and online presence, engaging in discussions and debates on topics such as religion, identity politics, and academic integrity.

Mike Holtz is a co-founder and content creator of WeWatchedAMovie, a YouTube channel dedicated to reviewing and discussing movies. With an energetic and engaging on-screen presence, Mike delivers entertaining and often humorous movie reviews, trailer reactions, and discussions on various pop culture topics.

Julian Gewirtz is a prominent economist and scholar, widely known for his work on the transformative economic reforms in China. A graduate of Harvard and Oxford, Gewirtz has earned recognition for his analytical insights into China's transition to a market-based economy and its global implications. His writings have appeared in top-tier academic journals and media outlets. He authored the acclaimed book "Unlikely Partners: Chinese Reformers, Western Economists, and the Making of Global China," which offers a comprehensive analysis of the cross-cultural exchange of economic ideas. He previously served in the Obama administration and has been Senior Fellow for China Studies at the Council on Foreign Relations. He's a lecturer in history at Harvard University and Columbia University.

Gabriel Barkay is a renowned Israeli archaeologist, born in 1944 in Hungary. A professor emeritus at Bar Ilan University, he is best known for his excavations in Jerusalem, especially at the Ketef Hinnom site where he discovered the oldest known copies of biblical text. He's the co-founder of the Temple Mount Sifting Project. Barkay's work, significantly contributing to our understanding of ancient Jerusalem, has earned him the prestigious Israel Prize for Archaeology in 1996. His commitment to archaeological research and teaching makes him a vital figure in the study of the history and archaeology of the Holy Land.

Thyssen is a recreational composer inclined towards ambient, experimental, and classical styles of music. He's fascinated with the evolution of music across history. His philosophical interests include Descartes, Heidegger, Jung, Nietzsche, Deleuze and others. He's studying neuroscience and believes intuition is a product of lower frequencies and core parts of the brain that are timeless and rooted in the collective unconscious. He's written a research paper on panpsychism and its scientific merit, and explores the notion of the universe being consciously interconnected through quantum effects.

Dave Soldier is an American composer, musician, and neuroscientist. He has defied musical boundaries by blending classical, jazz, rock, and avant-garde styles. As a founding member of the Soldier String Quartet, he gained acclaim for innovative performances with artists like Ornette Coleman. Alongside his musical pursuits, Soldier holds a Ph.D. in neuroscience from Columbia University. He has combined his scientific expertise with his artistic sensibilities, creating personalized symphonies based on individuals' DNA sequences. With collaborations ranging from the Thai Elephant Orchestra to the Kropotkins rock band, Soldier's multidisciplinary approach continues to challenge and inspire. His contributions to music and neuroscience make him a remarkable figure in both fields.

Cher, born Cherilyn Sarkisian in 1946, is an American singer, actress, and television personality. Over her six-decade career, she emerged as a pop culture icon with hits like "Believe" and "If I Could Turn Back Time." She's the only artist to have a number-one single on a Billboard chart in six different decades. Cher is also an acclaimed actress, earning an Academy Award for her performance in "Moonstruck" (1987). Her flamboyant style has made her a fashion influencer.

Justin Trudeau is a Canadian politician who has been serving as the Prime Minister since 2015. Born on December 25, 1971, he is the second-youngest Canadian Prime Minister, after Joe Clark. Trudeau, the leader of the Liberal Party, is noted for his progressive policies in the areas of health care, climate change, and social justice. Prior to entering politics, he was a teacher in Vancouver, British Columbia. He's the second child and first son of Pierre Trudeau, who was Prime Minister from 1968 to 1979, and then again from 1980 to 1984.

King Charles III, born Charles Philip Arthur George on November 14, 1948, is the reigning monarch of the United Kingdom since 2023. He previously held the title of Prince of Wales, and is recognized for his philanthropic work and interest in sustainable development. A passionate environmentalist, his reign is marked by advocacy for climate change action and conservation. He's the eldest son of Queen Elizabeth II and the late Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.

Robert DuHamel, a visionary in vocational education, is the founder of Vocademy, a tuition-free online vocational school providing comprehensive courses to prepare individuals for careers such as Certified Electronics Technicians. DuHamel offers instruction in various subjects like Electronics Technology, Information Technology, and Fiber Optics Technology. His initiative, supported by donations and sponsors, is addressing the critical shortage of electronics technicians in various industries. DuHamel's courses also aid learners in preparing for relevant certification exams, further bolstering their career opportunities.

Roanna Chan, a former Clinical Psychology Registrar, is an experienced practitioner who once served at Nature and Nurtured Child Psychology and Peter Walker and Associates Adult Psychology. With degrees from UNSW and Sydney University, she demonstrated adeptness in managing a diverse clientele. Her career valued self-management, continued research, and self-care, underscoring the holistic approach to her practice.

Abdel Fattah el-Sisi is an Egyptian military and political leader, born on November 19, 1954. He served as the director of military intelligence before seizing power in a 2013 coup against President Mohamed Morsi. Subsequently, el-Sisi was elected President in 2014 and re-elected in 2018, despite human rights concerns. He has focused on economic development, security and countering Islamist extremism in Egypt, but his leadership is controversial due to allegations of authoritarianism.

Noam Chomsky, born on December 7, 1928, is an American linguist, philosopher, cognitive scientist, historian, and social critic. He revolutionized the field of linguistics with his theory of transformational grammar and is often called the "father of modern linguistics." Chomsky is also renowned for his outspoken criticisms of US foreign policy, media, and capitalism, positioning him as a prominent figure in contemporary intellectual and political discourse.

Frank Turek's a renowned American Christian apologist, author, and public speaker. He co-authored "I Don't Have Enough Faith to be an Atheist" with Norman Geisler, advocating for the logical and scientific validity of Christian faith. Turek is the founder and president of CrossExamined.org, an organization aiming to address popular misconceptions about Christianity. His work emphasizes rational discourse, intellectual engagement, and the application of apologetics in everyday life.

Courtney Violetta, known for her YouTube channel "The Aurora Codes," is a spiritual mentor and wellness enthusiast. She creates content to aid viewers in understanding and embodying their higher selves. Topics span from spiritual awakenings, connection with spirit guides, shadow work, to the significance of names and personal transformations. Her videos also delve into exploring psychic abilities, interpreting dreams, and holistic healing practices. Courtney's primary goal is to help individuals reclaim their power, rediscover their magic, and align with their higher purpose.

L. Ron Hubbard (1911-1986) was an American author and the founder of the Church of Scientology. He gained fame for his science fiction and fantasy writing before developing the religious movement of Scientology in the 1950s. Hubbard's teachings and practices formed the basis of Scientology's beliefs and practices, which have been a subject of controversy over the years. He remains a polarizing figure, with supporters praising his contributions and critics questioning the validity and impact of his work.

Dianna Cowern, known popularly as "Physics Girl," is an esteemed science communicator and educator. An MIT physics graduate, she gained prominence for her YouTube channel where she demystifies complex physics concepts through engaging, easy-to-understand videos. With a passion for inspiring young people, especially girls, in STEM fields, Cowern also works with PBS Digital Studios and has been recognized for her contribution to science education and communication.

Sir Roger Penrose is an eminent British mathematical physicist, recognized for his pioneering contributions to general relativity and cosmology. Born in 1931, Penrose's work has significantly deepened our understanding of the universe. Notably, he co-developed the Penrose-Hawking singularity theorems in collaboration with Stephen Hawking. In 2020, he was awarded half of the Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery that black hole formation is a robust prediction of general relativity. Penrose's creative ideas continue to influence the fields of mathematics, physics, and philosophy of mind.

Elizabeth Olsen is an American actress known for her versatile performances in film and television. She gained prominence for her role as Wanda Maximoff/Scarlet Witch in the Marvel Cinematic Universe. Olsen's acting is characterized by emotional depth and range, and she's received critical acclaim for her work in both independent and blockbuster projects. Her contributions to the entertainment industry have solidified her as a respected and accomplished figure in Hollywood.

Andrew Hozier-Byrne, known as Hozier, is an Irish singer-songwriter and musician. He gained worldwide recognition with his debut single "Take Me to Church," known for its powerful vocals and socially conscious lyrics. Hozier's soulful voice and folk-rock style have earned him acclaim in the music industry. He explores themes of love, spirituality, and societal issues through his music, creating a unique blend of emotion and depth.

Clint Mansell, British musician and acclaimed film composer, transformed the cinematic soundscape with emotive scores. Born in 1963, Mansell began with UK band Pop Will Eat Itself before transitioning to film. His compelling works, notably in Darren Aronofsky's films such as "Requiem for a Dream," established him as an industry titan.

Gillian Welch is an esteemed American singer-songwriter and musician known for her exceptional talent in the realm of folk and Americana music. Born in 1967 in New York City, Welch developed a deep appreciation for traditional music at an early age. Her journey led her to Nashville, where she met her musical collaborator, David Rawlings. Together, they crafted a remarkable body of work, marked by hauntingly beautiful melodies and introspective lyrics that explore themes of love, loss, and the human experience. Welch's distinctive voice, coupled with her intricate guitar playing, creates a captivating atmosphere that transports listeners to a bygone era. With critically acclaimed albums like "Revival," "Time (The Revelator)," and "The Harrow & The Harvest," Gillian Welch has become an icon in the world of folk music, captivating audiences with her raw authenticity and timeless artistry.

Bob Burnquist is a legendary Brazilian professional skateboarder and philanthropist, widely recognized as one of the greatest skateboarders of all time. His innovative and daring style, combined with his impressive array of tricks, has earned him numerous titles and awards throughout his career, including 30 X Games medals. Burnquist is also well known from the Tony Hawk's Pro Skater video game series, where he is considered one of the most iconic and beloved characters. Beyond skateboarding, Burnquist is a committed environmentalist, and he has used his influence and resources to promote sustainability and environmental awareness.

Titus Welliver is an American actor known for his versatile performances in both film and television. Born in 1961, Welliver has built a successful career by portraying diverse characters across various genres. He has appeared in acclaimed TV shows such as "Deadwood," "Sons of Anarchy," and "The Good Wife," showcasing his range and talent. Welliver is perhaps best recognized for his portrayal of the titular character in the crime drama series "Bosch," based on Michael Connelly's popular novels. His portrayal of the relentless and complex detective Harry Bosch has earned him critical praise and a dedicated fan base. With his commanding presence, depth of characterization, and strong performances, Titus Welliver continues to leave a lasting impact on the screen.

Highly accomplished entrepreneur and digital marketer, known for his expertise in e-commerce and online business. He has achieved notable success in a relatively short period, establishing a reputation for strategic insights and adaptability in the ever-changing digital landscape. Welch has made significant contributions through his ventures and mentorship programs, assisting numerous individuals in building profitable online businesses.

M.I.A. (real name Mathangi "Maya" Arulpragasam) is a British rapper, singer, songwriter, visual artist and film maker. In the mid-2000s she rose to international fame with her politically charged and genre-blending music, most notably with her single, "Paper Planes". Known for her outspokenness, M.I.A.'s lyrics often address topics such as social activism, politics, identity, global issues, cultural and political injustices, and challenging social norms. Alongside her music career, M.I.A. is recognized for her artistic contributions, provocative visual aesthetics, and global influence being named one of the top 75 most influential people of the 21st century by Esquire magazine.

Nils Frahm is a German musician and composer known for his unique blend of classical, electronic, and experimental music. His compositions often feature rich textures, intricate melodies, and a delicate balance between minimalism and grandeur. Frahm's approach to music is characterized by his improvisational and dynamic style with the ability to create immersive and emotionally evocative soundscapes. His multiple acclaimed albums and mesmerizing live performances have garnered him a devoted following and critical recognition.

Dave Bayley, born June 7, 1989, is best known as the lead vocalist of British indie rock band, Glass Animals. Born in Massachusetts, he grew up in Oxford, England, where he formed the band in 2010. A neuroscientist by education, Bayley's eclectic musical influences range from hip hop to indie rock, resulting in Glass Animals' unique psychedelic pop sound. Despite career-threatening challenges, he led the band to global recognition with his innovative songwriting and production.

Sanaë Lemoine is a French-American author known for her eloquent and prose writing style in her debut novel "The Margot Affair." Lemoine explores the complexities of identity, relationships, and family secrets through keen observation and nuanced storytelling. Her writing focuses on portraying the emotional depth of her characters, making their journeys resonate with readers. With her unique narrative voice and lyrical control, Lemoine has established herself as a promising talent in the world of literature.

Scott Aaronson is an American computer scientist and theoretical physicist known for his work in the field of quantum computing and complexity theory. Aaronson has made significant contributions to quantum algorithms and has explored the philosophical implications of quantum mechanics, particularly related to computational complexity. He serves as a professor at the University of Texas at Austin and actively communicates complex scientific concepts to the general public through his blog and lectures, making him a prominent figure in science communication.

Heather Baron-Gracie is a British musician and lead vocalist and guitarist of the indie rock band Pale Waves. The band gained popularity with their dreamy and nostalgic sound, drawing influences from 80s pop and alternative rock. Baron-Gracie's introspective nature and vulnerability are evident in her lyrics, which explore themes of love, heartbreak, and personal struggles. With her dynamic stage presence and unique fashion sense, she has become an influential figure in the indie music scene.

Nina Kraviz is a Russian DJ, producer, and singer who is known for her energetic DJ sets that blend various sub-genres of techno and house music. Her DJ sets are often described as dynamic, captivating, and immersive experiences. She has a unique talent for creating an intense and hypnotic atmosphere on the dancefloor drawing listeners into her sonic journey. With her infectious personality and fun-loving approach to life, Nina Kraviz continues to be a prominent figure in the electronic music scene.

Sorelle Amore is an Australian photographer, filmmaker, and social media influencer known for her empowering content focused on self-love, personal development, and financial literacy. With a strong emphasis on promoting body positivity and self-acceptance, she inspires her audience through authentic storytelling and motivational messages. Through her engaging vlogs and social media presence, Sorelle encourages individuals to embrace their uniqueness, pursue their passions, and cultivate a positive mindset for personal growth and fulfillment.

Mustafa Al-Bassam is a cybersecurity researcher and computer scientist known for his early involvement with the hacktivist group LulzSec. At a young age, he was part of operations that targeted various organizations, including corporations and government agencies. After facing legal repercussions, he turned to a more constructive path, focusing on cybersecurity research and ethical hacking. Mustafa has contributed to academic research in the field of computer security, spoken at several industry conferences, and worked on initiatives to improve online privacy and security. His journey from hacktivist to researcher offers a unique perspective on the ethical dimensions of cybersecurity.

Brennan Lee Mulligan is a writer, actor, and game master known for his work in the field of tabletop role-playing games. He gained recognition for his role as the Dungeon Master in the web series "Dimension 20" by CollegeHumor. Mulligan is celebrated for his storytelling abilities, dynamic character portrayals, and his talent for creating immersive and engaging game worlds. His passion for the medium and his ability to captivate audiences have made him a beloved figure in the tabletop RPG community.

George Thompson is a YouTuber who delves into Eastern philosophy on his channel. With a keen interest in various Eastern teachings, including Taoism, Buddhism, and Confucianism, he shares profound insights on mindfulness, self-discovery, and personal growth. Through his thought-provoking videos, George encourages viewers to embrace ancient wisdom, find inner peace, and lead fulfilling lives in alignment with Eastern principles. His content has garnered a dedicated community seeking spiritual guidance and philosophical understanding.

Yungblud (real name Dominic Richard Harrison) is a British singer, songwriter, and musician known for his high-energy performances and socially conscious lyrics. Yungblud rose to prominence in the late 2010s with his fusion of punk rock, pop, and hip-hop influences. His music often addresses themes of youth rebellion, mental health, and social issues, resonating with a generation seeking an outlet for their frustrations and aspirations. Yungblud's passionate and charismatic stage presence, along with his bold fashion choices, have helped him cultivate a strong connection with his fanbase and make a strong impact on the 2020s alternative music scene.

Greg Puciato is a multifaceted musician and artist known for his dynamic contributions to the music industry. He is a skilled vocalist and songwriter, recognized for his work with bands such as The Dillinger Escape Plan and Killer Be Killed. Puciato's musical versatility and intense stage presence have earned him a reputation as a prominent figure in the world of alternative and heavy music.

Anderson Silva, a Brazilian mixed martial artist and boxer, is widely regarded as the greatest of all time in MMA. He held the UFC Middleweight Championship and set a record for the longest title reign in UFC history at 2,457 days. His remarkable career showcases his dominance in the middleweight division, solidifying his legacy as one of MMA's greatest fighters.

Melvin Manhoef, a retired Dutch fighter, excelled in kickboxing and MMA. He held the It's Showtime Middleweight title in kickboxing and the Cage Rage Light Heavyweight title in MMA. Manhoef competed in multiple organizations, including Bellator, Strikeforce, DREAM, and more. He's renowned for his knockout prowess, with 29 of his 32 wins ending in knockouts, a record among fighters with 15 wins. Manhoef also founded the World Fighting League, a kickboxing and MMA promotion.

Thomas Sowell is an American economist, social theorist, and senior fellow at Stanford University's Hoover Institution. Born in 1930 in North Carolina, he rose from a poor upbringing to earn degrees from Harvard, Columbia, and the University of Chicago. Known for his conservative views, Sowell has written extensively on social issues, economics, and political thought, authoring over 30 books and countless articles. His works such as "Basic Economics," "The Vision of the Anointed," and "Intellectuals and Society" have been influential in shaping conservative thought. He is highly regarded for his lucid prose and ability to dissect complex issues.

Frank Caprio is an American lawyer and judge known for his role as a municipal court judge in Providence, Rhode Island. He gained widespread recognition for his compassionate and unconventional approach to justice, which often involves levying reduced fines or dismissing cases altogether. Caprio's courtroom proceedings have been featured on the television show "Caught in Providence," showcasing his commitment to fairness and humanity. He is regarded as a symbol of empathy within the legal system, using his position to make a positive impact on people's lives and challenge traditional norms of judicial practice.

Hilary Putnam (1926–2016) was an influential American philosopher known for his work in philosophy of mind, language, and mathematics. A central figure in Western philosophy during the 20th century, he contributed significantly to the development of philosophical realism and functionalism. Putnam notably challenged conventional thinking through his "multiple realizability" thesis and "brains in a vat" thought experiment. An intellectual chameleon, he frequently revised his philosophical stance, earning him a reputation for breadth of thought and continual self-critique.

Visionary entrepreneur and bioengineer who left an indelible mark on the world of synthetic biology. He displayed an early fascination with science and technology, which eventually led him to co-found Cambrian Genomics in 2011. As CEO of the company, Heinz aimed to revolutionize the field of DNA synthesis by developing affordable and accessible gene-editing technologies. His groundbreaking work included pioneering the use of laser-printing DNA, which significantly reduced the cost and time required for genetic engineering. Heinz's innovative approach garnered attention and acclaim, earning him recognition as a trailblazer in the biotech industry.

Aesop Rock is an American rapper known for his metaphorically dense and cryptic lyricism. His thought-provoking lyrics often touch on themes of introspection, societal issues, and human psychology. Aesop Rock has released several critically acclaimed albums, showcasing his exceptional wordplay and storytelling abilities. He has been praised for his innovative and complex approach to rap music, solidifying his place as a prominent figure in the underground hip-hop scene.

Billy Doyle is a prominent teacher of the Kashmir Shaivism tradition of non-dual meditation. He gained recognition for his unique approach in combining traditional Eastern practices with modern Western sensibilities. After years of exploring yoga and undergoing spiritual transformation, he studied under Jean Klein, a renowned spiritual teacher. Through his workshops, retreats, and books, Billy Doyle has been guiding individuals worldwide in accessing the deeper layers of consciousness and self-awareness.

Max Cooper is a British electronic music producer, DJ, and scientist known for his intricate and complex musical compositions. With a background in computational biology, he combines science and music to create unique and ambitious audiovisual experiences. Cooper's music blends ambient, techno, and experimental elements, reflecting his deep understanding of complex systems and patterns found in nature. His compositions take listeners on a mesmerizing journey through the intersection of science and art.

Remy Bonjasky is a Dutch former kickboxer and three-time K-1 World Grand Prix champion. Known for his dynamic fighting style and powerful kicks, Bonjasky achieved prominence in the heavyweight division. Beyond his success in the ring, he's recognized for his sportsmanship and charisma. Retired in 2014, Bonjasky left an indelible mark on kickboxing, earning a place among the sport's legends.

Lauren Tsai is a multifaceted artist known for her talents as a model, actress, and illustrator. Born in 1998 in Massachusetts, she rose to fame through her appearance on the reality show "Terrace House: Aloha State." Her unique blend of creativity led her to become a sought-after figure in the fashion industry, securing modeling contracts with major brands. Beyond modeling, she showcased her acting skills in the hit series "Legion." Additionally, Tsai is an accomplished illustrator, with her artwork reflecting a dark and imaginative style.

Lee Ji-eun, known professionally as IU, is a South Korean singer-songwriter and actress, born on May 16, 1993. She has gained widespread acclaim for her versatile musical styles, from ballads to indie-pop, and her emotive vocal delivery. Since her debut album “Lost and Found” in 2008, IU has become one of the most celebrated and influential artists in Korea and beyond. Alongside her music career, she has successfully ventured into acting, starring in popular dramas such as “Moon Lovers: Scarlet Heart Ryeo” and “My Mister”. Her philanthropy and engagement with fans have also earned her admiration.

Jimmy Donaldson (MrBeast) is an American YouTuber, philanthropist, and entrepreneur who rose to prominence with his unique blend of entertaining and often extravagant content. Known for his jaw-dropping stunts, MrBeast has successfully captured the attention of millions with videos featuring large cash giveaways, expensive challenges, and acts of kindness.
